title: Inside the Bureau: Careers Beyond Corrections (Health, Business, Psychology & MORE!)
description:
Think the Federal Bureau of Prisons is just about the Correctional pathway? Think again!

Join Jennifer Johnson, Recruitment Specialist from the National Recruitment Office and representative from U.S. Penitentiary Atwater, for an in-depth info session introducing the wide range of career opportunities available across the Bureau — right here in California and nationwide. From roles in psychology, medical services, and business operations to positions in dentistry, recruitment, paramedics, and beyond, the BOP offers diverse, mission-driven paths for students from many academic backgrounds.

Whether you’re looking for meaningful public service work, exploring federal pathways, or just curious about the agency’s scope — this is your chance to ask questions, gain insights, and see where you might fit. 

 

Highlighted Pathways 💼

Psychology, sociology, social workBusiness, HR, and financePre-health, pre-med, or allied health fieldsPublic service and federal careersBring a peer, come with questions, leave with a new perspective — you never know what may be your calling!

 

Register Here: https://ucmerced.joinhandshake.com/edu/events/1748504

 

UC Merced’s Career Center is pleased to make this program known to our students and alumni. This is an event hosted by an external organization and included because it may be of interest to members of our University community.  Inclusion does not indicate University sponsorship or endorsement.

title: Grammar Masters Workshop: Avoiding Verb Agreement Errors
description:
Grammar Masters Workshop: Avoiding Verb Agreement Errors

 

Thursday, Sept. 18, 12:00-12:50pm, in Granite Pass #145

 

Can you spot the error below?

 

The company's CEO, as well as his administrative staff, were asked to resign due to mismanagement of investor funds.

 

Come practice recognizing when nouns and the verbs that follow them do and do not agree, even in long, complex sentences and when lengthy phrases come between the subjects and verbs. We'll also spend a little time making sure vague pronouns like "it" agree with the nouns they refer to.  This workshop is open to whole the campus community.

 

Sponsored by the English Language Institute (ELI). For more information, send email to eli@ucmerced.edu. View this semester's workshop schedule at http://eli.ucmerced.edu/grammar-workshops.

title: MTS Series Speaker: Erica Cartmill
description:
Cognitive and Information Sciences' Mind, Technology, and Society (MTS) Speaker Series presents Erica Cartmill, Professor of Cognitive Science, Anthropology, & Animal Science at Indiana University.

 

Cartmill will present on "Play and Projection: Social and Physical Problem Solving in Great Apes".

 

Description:

The ability to anticipate events and project outcomes is crucial for creative problem solving in many species, including humans. Simulation of possible futures is difficult to prove in biological systems but may often be the best way to explain behavior. Play behavior in particular, likely involves rehearsal and testing of possible outcomes in a low(er) stakes environment. In this talk, I examine two areas in which great apes might productively use projection and play: teasing and tool use. I present our work on playful teasing, a behavior between play and aggression, in which apes explore, test, and advertise their social relationships. I then discuss an in-progress study on physical cognition using a video game interface to test how apes select and apply tools to solve physical tasks. Together, these studies help reveal the complex ways non-human primates strategically and creatively navigate their social and physical environments.

 

Students, faculty, and staff are welcome to attend!

title: CALLING ALL ENGINEERS: Lunch + Learn with Webcor Builders!
description:
Looking for an internship that’s more than just coffee runs and spreadsheets?

Webcor, one of the industry's top commercial builders, offers an internship program that puts students on real project teams- learning directly from construction pros and gaining hands-on experience that actually matters. They’re known for a culture of collaboration, innovation, and transparency; and for building some pretty incredible things.

In fact, they helped build our campus. Webcor was THE lead builder on the UC Merced 2020 Project: an award-winning project, as well as the largest higher education expansion of its kind in North America. And they love hiring Bobcats like you! Our partnership has already opened doors for many UC Merced students. You could be next.

Join the info session to learn about the internship roles they’re hiring for and the full-time opportunities available after graduation. Plus, yes- there will be free pizza. 🍕

title: UC Carpentries Fall Workshop Series: Coding and Data Management
description:
This 9-day workshop series aims to teach participants basic concepts, skills, and tools for R in RStudio, Python in Jupyter Notebook, an introduction to the Unix Shell, Version Control with Git, SQL, and Tidy Data. This workshop is designed for researchers and enables non-experts to develop computing skills for research analysis. The workshops are free and open to all UC students, staff, postdocs, and faculty.

 

The workshops will be held on Zoom, September 15th – 25th, 8:30 am – 12:30 pm. Participants are free to sign up for any combination of workshops they find useful.

 

For more information and to register, visit: https://jmjamison.github.io/2025-09-15-UC/

title: Faculty Author Series: Dr. Daniel K. Thompson
description:
Please join us for an author talk featuring Assistant Professor of Anthropology, Daniel K. Thompson. 

 

In this talk, Dr. Thompson will discuss his new book, Smugglers, Speculators, and the City in the Ethiopia-Somalia Borderlands. The book explores the work of Ethiopian-Somali smugglers and investors and examines links between cities and borders in rapid urbanization.  

 

Event Time: Noon-1pm 

Event Date: Thursday, September 25, 2025 

Event Location: Kolligian Library Building, KL 232 

 

Registration is encouraged as seating is limited. Light refreshments provided. We will give away a few copies of the book during the event.

title: 2025 UC Merced Student Leadership Conference
description:
SAVE THE DATE: Friday, September 26th, 2025 3PM - 8PM in Lakireddy Grand Ballroom - Conference Center at UC Merced. 

The annual UC Merced Leadership Conference is one of the longest-running conferences at UC Merced! The annual conference brings together students, alumni, and guest speakers for a full day in which students learn from speakers the many strategies and skills necessary to engage in leadership and remain life-long learners.  Every year, The Souza Leadership Center brings inspiring speakers who have learned to overcome challenges to find their voice and their confidence as leaders.

Questions? Contact us at Lead@ucmerced.edu 

Conference Theme: The Leadership Multiverse: Connecting with IntegrityFor better or worse, we are living in a world shaped by the leaders who came before us—and today, we are shaping the future for those who will come after us. Our actions matter. Whether we recognize it or not, we are part of a deeply connected society. That’s why it’s essential to lead and connect with integrity. 

Our theme acknowledges the complexity of our current world—where connection and division often coexist—and calls on student leaders to lead with vision, empathy, and authenticity. “The Leadership Multiverse” represents the many dimensions in which leadership occurs today: on campus, online, within communities, across cultures, and within ourselves.

 

The Student Leadership conference will feature workshops on authentic leadership, identity, leadership and much more! Registration will open soon, all are welcome to attend! 

 RSVP link - https://studentleadership.ucmerced.edu/conference Learn more at http://ucmerced.presence.io/event/2025-uc-merced-student-leadership-conference
